Centre for culture and friendship with DPRK opens in Mongolia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 26 (KCNA) -- An opening ceremony of the centre for culture and friendship with the DPRK took place in Ulaan Baatar on July 17.
 On display at the ceremony place were photos showing the leadership feats of President Kim Il Sung and leader Kim Jong Il and their famous works and Korean handiworks.
 Speeches were made at the ceremony.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 S. Surenjav, chairman of the Mongolia-Korea Friendship Society, addressing the ceremony, said that the centre will serve as a base to hold various political and cultural functions on important occasions including the birth anniversaries of Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A letter to Kim Jong Il was adopted there.

Functions held to mark anniversary of war victory 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 26 (KCNA) -- Functions were held in Pyongyang yesterday to mark the 48th anniversary of the victory in the great fatherland liberation war.
 A performance "song of eternal victory" was given at the central workers' hall with war veterans and honoured disabled soldiers participating in it. Through such songs as "Song of General Kim Il Sung," "Song of National Defence" and "To the Road of Decisive Battle" and numbers the performers successfully represented the exploits president kim il sung performed by winning the victory in the war and the feats made by the people's army and people of Korea in honourably defending the dignity and sovereignty of the nation under his leadership. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They truthfully depicted the Korean people's revolutionary spirit and unshakable will to build a powerful nation on this land without fail under the army-first leadership of Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, youth and students held a concert "July 27, Day of Victory" at the Central Youth Hall.

U.S. chiefly accountable for instability 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 26 (KCNA) -- Commander-in-chief of the U.S. forces in the Pacific Blair termed "North Korea one of the greatest threats to the stability in the Asian region" and called for "sustained emphasis on the Asian defence" to cope with it.
 In this regard Rodong Sinmun today in a signed commentary says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is non-sensible for the U.S. to talk about "threat" from someone. Its loudmouthed "threat" from the DPRK is a cock-and-bull story fabricated to retain its military edge in the Asian region. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the strategic aim of the U.S. imperialists' Asian policy to keep its troops in the region under the pretext of "guaranteeing stability" and retain their military edge there in a bid to contain other countries and go unchallenged in a war for interests and establish its political and military domination over the region.
 The U.S. call for putting emphasis on the Asian defence to "cope with the threat" from the DPRK means its intention to stay in the region under that pretext and retain its military edge there and thus continue aggression and interference in internal affairs of other countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The United States is keen to launch another war against the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Recently it staged war exercises one after another after deploying new task forces and sophisticated military hardware in and around South Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All these facts go to prove that the U.S. imperialists are the chief harasser of peace and stability in Asia.

Joint press statement between DPRK and EU released
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 26 (KCNA) -- A joint press statement on the establishment of diplomatic relations between the DPRK and EU was released today.
 The statement reads: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK Foreign Ministry ambassador at large, Ho Jong, and EU commission director Percy Westerlund met informally on July 25 in Hanoi to discuss follow-up to the establishment of diplomatic relations between the DPRK and EU. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The diplomatic relations were established on May 14th 2001, following an exchange of letters between DPRK foreign minister Paek Nam Sun and EU external relations commissioner Christopher Patten. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was agreed that the practical details of diplomatic representation would be negotiated this autumn.
